{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501417"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:29:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:29:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1759"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.48,0.07,0.34,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37193"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"472"},{"type":"tags","id":"913"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4237"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43851"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents with rash  which has been ongoing for several weeks.  The rash consists of non-blanching petechiae and palpable purpura on the anterior surface of both lower legs. He has a known history of Child\u0027s Pugh C liver cirrhosis, alcohol abuse, and untreated hepatitis C. A biopsy of the skin lesions demonstrates small vessel inflammation with immune deposits in the vascular walls.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following results is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevated complement levels","Positive Anti-neutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies (ANCA)","Thrombocytosis","Cryoglobulinemia","Neutrophilia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation and biopsy findings are in keeping with \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed cryoglobulinaemic vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E, a key extrahepatic manifestations of hepatitis C infection. Extra-hepatic manifestations are relatively common in hepatitis C infection, although this is decreasing with the widespread use of direct-acting antivirals. Other known extrahepatic manifestations of chronic hepatitis C infection include autoimmune disorders, lymphoproliferative disorders and Type 2 diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryoglobulinaemic vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a lymphoproliferative disorder that leads to deposition of circulating immune complexes in small to medium size blood vessels resulting in a leucocytoclastic vasculitis. More than 90 percent of patients with essential mixed cryoglobulinemia are HCV infected. Other manifestations of this condition include arthralgia, renal disease, neurologic disease, and hypocomplementemia. Peripheral neuropathies may also result, often in an asymmetric pattern. Treatment of HCV with direct-acting antivirals may lead to complete or partial remission of the vasculitis, although immunosuppression and other treatments may be required in more severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated complement levels \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be in keeping with cryoglobulinaemia. Complement levels can be reduced in cryoglobulinaemia due to destruction by cryoglobulin-containing immune complexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EANCA \u003C/strong\u003Emay be positive in other vasculitides, cryoglobulinaemic vasculitis is an ANCA-negative vasculitis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApparent \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombocytosis \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eneutrophilia \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be present in cryoglobulinaemia due to measurement errors related to cryoglobulin particles, but these are non-specific, non-diagnostic findings. Thrombocytopaenia is also frequent in the setting of chronic liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cryoglobulinaemia is one of the most common extra-hepatic manifestations of hepatitis C infection"],"references":["Charles ED, Dustin LB. Hepatitis C virus\u2013induced cryoglobulinemia. Kidney international. 2009 Oct 2;76(8):818-24.","Saadoun D. Extrahepatic manifestations of chronic HCV infection. N Engl J Med. 2021;384(11):1038-1052."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37193"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1759"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37193"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T11:58:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T07:33:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51886"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":